The racial disparities that have plagued the cruel and uneven toll of the coronavirus across parts of the nation appear to be emerging in California.
“The pandemic happens on top of big inequities in health that already exist,” said Kirsten Bibbins-Domingo, vice dean for Population Health and Health Equity at UCSF.
The death rate for Asian Americans is 2.1 per 100,000.
The Latino community’s low death rate, however, comes as the group’s caseload is much higher and more representative of its share of the population.
The number of cases among black residents, meanwhile, was about 6% of cases, on par with their population representation.